{"rawJson":null,"m_plot":null,"m_cast":null,"m_reception":"The film received universal acclaim, holding a 95% \"Fresh\" rating on film review aggregate website Rotten Tomatoes and 85 out of 100 on Metacritic.[4][5] | One of the scenes near the end of the film was excised from the international version of the film, likely due to its animal cruelty.[6] | The critic Roger Ebert included the film in his list of great movies.[7]","m_production":"Kim Ki-duk said of the film: \"I intended to portray the joy, anger, sorrow and pleasure of our lives through four seasons and through the life of a monk who lives in a temple on Jusan Pond surrounded only by nature.\"[3] | \"The hermitage that is the stage for Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring is an artificially constructed set made to float on top of Jusanji Pond in Cheongsong County, North Gyeongsang Province in South Korea. Created about 200 years ago, Jusanji Pond (36°21′45.70″N 129°11′22.91″E﻿ / ﻿36.3626944°N 129.1896972°E﻿ / 36.3626944; 129.1896972) is an artificial lake in which the surrounding mountains are reflected in its waters. It retains the mystical aura of having trees more than one hundred years old still growing along its shores. LJ Film was able to obtain permission to build the set after finally convincing the Ministry of Environment through six months of negotiations.\"[3]","m_sequel":null,"m_based_on":null,"m_directed_by":"Kim Ki-duk","m_produced_by":"Karl Baumgartner Lee Seung-jae","m_screenplay_by":null,"m_story_by":null,"m_starring":"Oh Yeong-su Kim Young-min Seo Jae-kyung Kim Jong-ho Ha Yeo-jin","m_music_by":"Bark Jee-woong","m_cinematography":"Baek Dong-hyeon","m_edited_by":"Kim Ki-duk","m_production_company":null,"m_distributed_by":"Cineclick Asia","m_release_dates":"September 19, 2003 (2003-09-19) |  |  |  | ","m_running_time":"103 minutes","m_country":"South Korea Germany","m_language":"Korean","m_budget":null,"m_box_office":"$9,524,745 | Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring (also known as Spring, Summer, Autumn, Winter... and Spring) is a 2003 South Korean film directed by Kim Ki-duk about a Buddhist monastery that floats on a lake in a pristine forest. The story is about the life of a Buddhist monk as he passes through the seasons of his life, from childhood to old age. | The film stars Su Oh-yeong, Kim Young-min, Seo Jae-kyung and Kim Jong-ho. The director himself appears as the man in the last stage of life. This quiet, contemplative film marked a significant change from his previous works, which were often criticized for excessive violence and misogyny. The film was released in the United States in 2004 by Sony Pictures Classics, in subtitle format. |  | ","m_marketing":null,"m_reference":"^ a b c Buddhist Wheel of Life at BBC Religion and Ethics—In Pictures. Retrieved 30 May 2014 | ^ a b Traditional Patterns—Animals at Life in Korea. Retrieved 30 May 2014 | ^ a b \"Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring\". Sony Classics. 2004. Retrieved March 27, 2014.  | ^ \"Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring Reviews, Pictures - Rotten Tomatoes\". Retrieved 2010-07-29.  | ^ \"Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring (2004) - Reviews\". Retrieved 2008-04-23.  | ^ \"Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring (Comparison: International Version - Original Version) - Movie-Censorship.com\".  | ^ \"Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring - Roger Ebert Review\". Chicago Sun-Times. Retrieved 2009-08-26. ","m_external_link":"Official website | Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring at the Internet Movie Database | Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring at AllMovie | Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring at Box Office Mojo | Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... And Spring at HanCinema | Review of Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring at The New York Times | Review at koreanfilm.org","m_poster":"Pom yŏrŭm kaŭl kyŏul kŭrigo pom","m_production_companies":null,"m_written_by":"Kim Ki-duk"}